# Code owners — ATTENTION ROUTING, not a security boundary.
#
# Be honest about what this does. Agents currently commit and open PRs using
# the maintainer's own GitHub identity, so an agent IS the code owner and can
# satisfy any review requirement here. Against a confused or hijacked agent
# this stops nothing. What it does do is force the question "why is this PR
# touching that file?" at the moment of merge, which is worth having.
#
# (The change that would give this teeth is a separate GitHub identity for
# agents. Then GitHub's own self-approval prohibition does real work and every
# gate below acquires meaning. Until then, read the list as a checklist, not a
# lock.)
#
# SELECTION RULE: own the paths where the diff does not show the danger, or
# where a mistake is irreversible. Deliberately NOT everything — a review you
# always approve is worse than no review, because it launders unread changes
# as reviewed.

# --- the release mechanism -------------------------------------------------
# npm's trusted publisher binds to a workflow FILENAME, not its contents:
# whoever can edit release.yml can publish anything as @hedgerow/*.
/.github/                   @crsren
# The release gates themselves. A one-line edit silently disables a control.
/scripts/                   @crsren
# Root package.json defines the gate CHAIN: `release` is
# `verify:packaging && api:check && check-changesets && changeset publish`.
# Rewriting it to just `changeset publish` disables every release-time gate
# without touching .github/ or scripts/.
/package.json               @crsren
# Cache keys decide whether a gate actually re-ran. Get `inputs`/
# `globalDependencies` wrong and api:check verifies the committed report
# against a stale dist/ and passes green.
/turbo.json                 @crsren
# One `registry=` line redirects every CI install — inside the job that mints
# the npm OIDC credential.
/.npmrc                     @crsren
# What publishes, at what version, under which dist-tag.
/.changeset/config.json     @crsren
/.changeset/pre.json        @crsren
# files / exports / publishConfig decide what actually reaches npm.
/packages/*/package.json    @crsren

# --- the irreversible one --------------------------------------------------
# Lexicons define records written into OTHER PEOPLE'S atproto repos, where they
# stay permanently and cannot be migrated. The behaviour contract catches
# CHANGES to a record shape; nothing catches a bad shape at introduction. This
# is the most irreversible artifact in the project — a burned version number is
# cheap by comparison.
/packages/publish/lexicons/ @crsren

# --- deliberately NOT owned ------------------------------------------------
# Recording these so an absence reads as a decision, not an oversight.
#
# /api-report/     Generated. api:check fails if it is stale, and the changeset
#                  gate already fails a `patch` that removes declarations. A
#                  review checkbox on a generated file is a click on something
#                  already mechanically enforced.
# pnpm-lock.yaml   The least reviewable diff in the repo — owning it buys a
#                  rubber stamp, and re-imposes approval on every Dependabot
#                  npm PR, which is the friction this scope exists to remove.
#                  Mitigated instead by `onlyBuiltDependencies` (no arbitrary
#                  postinstall) and dependabot's `cooldown` (never pull a
#                  version published hours ago).
